\id DAN Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h Daniel
\mt1 The Prophecy of Daniel.
\c 1
\p
\v 1 IN the third year of the kingdom of Joakim king of Juda, came Nabuchodonosor king of Babylon into Jerusalem, and besieged it. \f + \fr 1:1 \ft The first part. Acts of Daniel with the other three Hebrew children; & of the Kings of Babylon.\f* \x + \xo 1:1 \xt 4. Reg. 24. v. 1.\x*
\v 2 And our Lord delivered into his hand Joakim the king of Juda, and part of the vessels of the house of God: and he carried them away into the land of Sennaar, into the house of his god, & the vessels he brought into the house of the treasure of his god. \f + \fr 1:2 \ft Part of the holy vessels & some special persons were carried away, but the King was released at this time: for he reigned in Jerusalem eight years more, eleven in all. 2. Par. 36. v. 5.\f*
\v 3 And the king spake to Asphenez the governor of the Eunuchs, that he should bring in of the children of Israel, and of the king's, & the tyrants' seed,
\v 4 children in whom was no spot, beautiful of form, and instructed in all wisdom, cunning in knowledge, and taught in discipline, and that might stand in the king's palace, that he might teach them the learning, and the tongue of the Chaldees.
\v 5 And the king appointed them a certain provision for every day, of his meats, & of the wine whereof he drank himself, that being nourished three years, afterward they might stand in the king's sight.
\v 6 There were therefore among them of the children of Juda, Daniel, Ananias, Misael, and Azarias.
\v 7 And the governor of the eunuchs gave them names: to Daniel, Baltassar: to Ananias, Sidrach, to Misael, Misach: & to Azarias, Abdenago.
\v 8 But Daniel purposed in his heart, that he would not be polluted of the king's table, nor of the wine of his drink: & he requested the governor of the eunuchs, that he might not be contaminated. \f + \fr 1:8 \ft Daniel as chief was an example to the other three children in their manner of life, whereby is also probable that they being all of the tribe of Juda, v. 6. he was nearer of the royal blood: of which some were taken into the King's court. v. 3.\f*
\v 9 And God gave unto Daniel grace and mercy in the sight of the prince of the eunuchs.
\v 10 And the prince of the eunuchs said to Daniel: I fear my lord the king, who hath appointed for you meat and drink: who if he shall see your faces leaner than the other youths your equals, you shall condemn my head to the king.
\v 11 And Daniel said to Malasar whom the prince of the eunuchs appointed over Daniel, Ananias, Misael, and Azarias:
\v 12 Prove I beseech thee, thy servants for ten days, & let pulse be given us to eat, & water to drink: \f + \fr 1:12 \ft Three causes moved them to abstain from the King's meats: lest they might eat any thing offered to idols, or forbid by the law of Moyses, and because such delicate diet might provoke to gluttony, or in time when they should be elder, to other sins. Theod.\f* \f + \fr 1:12 \ft * beans, peas &c.\f*
\v 13 and look upon our faces, and the faces of the children that eat of the king's meat: and as thou shalt see, thou shalt do with thy servants.
\v 14 Who hearing that manner of speech, proved them for ten days.
\v 15 And after ten days their faces appeared better & more corpulent than all the children, that did eat of the king's meat.
\v 16 Moreover Malasar took away the meats, and the wine of their drink: and he gave them pulse.
\v 17 And to these children God gave knowledge, and discipline in every book, and wisdom: but to Daniel the understanding of all visions and dreams.
\v 18 The days therefore being accomplished, after which the king had said, that they should be brought in; the governor of the eunuchs brought them in the sight of Nabuchodonosor.
\v 19 And when the king had spoken to them, there were not found such of them all, as Daniel, Ananias, Misael, and Azarias: and they stood in the king's sight.
\v 20 And every word of wisdom and understanding, that the king demanded of them, he found in them more by ten fold above all the soothsayers, & magicians, that were in all his kingdom.
\v 21 And Daniel was even to the first year of Cyrus the king. \f + \fr 1:21 \ft By mention of the first year of Cyrus is sufficiently signified that Daniel lived all the time of the captivity. And ch. 10. it is further clear that he lived in the third year: & very like longer.\f*
\c 2
\p
revelation, 24. telleth, 36. and interpreteth the dream: 46. \add the King adoreth him, confessing his God to be the only true God, and advanceth him & his fellows.\add*
\v 1 IN the second year of the kingdom of Nabuchodonosor, Nabuchodonosor saw a dream, and his spirit was terrified, and his dream was fled from him. \f + \fr 2:1 \ft Nabuchodonosor had this dream the second year after his great conquest of the Moabites, Ammonites, Syrians, & Ægyptians, making his Kingdom a great Monarchy: so it was in the 25. year of his reign: when Daniel was about the age of 35 years.\f*
\v 2 But the king commanded, that the soothsayers should be called together, and the magicians, and the sorcerers, and the Chaldees: to declare unto the king his dreams: who when they were come, stood before the king. \f + \fr 2:2 \ft * professors of Astrology.\f*
\v 3 And the king said to them: I saw a dream: & being confounded in mind I know not what I saw.
\v 4 And the Chaldees answered the king in Syriach: King for ever live: tell the dream to thy servants, and we will declare the interpretation thereof.
\v 5 And the king answering said to the Chaldees. The word is departed from me: unless you tell me the dream, and the conjecture thereof, you shall perish, and your houses shall be confiscate.
\v 6 But if you tell the dream, & the conjecture thereof, you shall receive of me rewards, & gifts, and much honour: the dream therefore, and the interpretation thereof tell you me.
\v 7 They answered the second time, & said: Let the king tell his servants the dream, & we will declare the interpretation thereof.
\v 8 The king answered, & said: Surely I know that you redeem time, knowing that the word is departed from me.
\v 9 If therefore you shew me not the dream, there is one sentence of you, that you have also framed a guileful interpretation, and full of deceit, to speak unto me till the time pass away. Tell me therefore the dream, that I may know that you speak a true interpretation also thereof. \f + \fr 2:9 \ft It is indeed more easy to tell by the devil's help, what one hath dreamed; because dreams being past, might either proceed from the devil, or by some external signs be known unto him: but to declare the signification which is to come, and uncertain, is above the devil's or man's power: who can only conjecture what is probable, & do often err therein. See the Annot. Gen. 40.\f*
\v 10 The Chaldees therefore answering before the king, said: There is no man upon the earth, that can accomplish thy word, o king, yea neither any king great and mighty, demandeth such a word of any soothsayer, & magician, and Chaldee.
\v 11 For the word that thou askest, o king, is weighty: neither shall there be found any, that can shew it in sight of the king, except the gods, whose conversation is not with men.
\v 12 Which thing being heard, the king in fury, and in great wrath commanded that all the wisemen of Babylon should perish.
\v 13 And the sentence being gone forth, wisemen were slain: & Daniel and his fellows were sought for, to perish.
\v 14 Then Daniel inquired concerning the law, and the sentence, of Arioch the prince of the king's warfare, who was gone forth to kill the wisemen of Babylon.
\v 15 And he asked him, that had received the power of the king, for what cause so cruel a sentence was gone forth from the face of the king. When Arioch therefore had shewed the matter to Daniel,
\v 16 Daniel going in desired the king, that he would give him a time to tell the solution to the king.
\v 17 And he went into his house, and he told the matter unto Ananias, & Misael, & Azarias his fellows:
\v 18 that they should ask mercy at the face of the God of heaven upon this sacrament, & Daniel and his fellows might not perish, with the rest of the wisemen of Babylon.
\v 19 Then was the mystery revealed to Daniel by a vision in the night: and Daniel blessed the God of heaven,
\v 20 and speaking said: The name of our Lord be blessed from everlasting & for ever more: because wisdom and strength are his.
\v 21 And he changeth times, and ages: transporteth kingdoms & establisheth them: giveth wisdom to the wise, and knowledge to them that understand discipline:
\v 22 he revealeth profound & hidden things, and knoweth the things that are done in darkness: and light is with him.
\v 23 To thee o God of our fathers I confess, and I praise thee: Because thou hast given me wisdom, & strength: and now thou hast shewed me the things that we desired of thee, because the king's word thou hast opened to us.
\v 24 After these things Daniel being entered in to Arioch, whom the king had appointed to destroy the wisemen of Babylon, spake thus unto him: Destroy not the wisemen of Babylon: bring me in before the presence of the king, & I will tell the solution to the king.
\v 25 Then Arioch in haste brought in Daniel to the king, and said to him: I have found a man of the children of the transmigration of Juda, that can tell the solution to the king.
\v 26 The king answered, and said to Daniel, whose name was Baltassar: Thinkest thou in very deed thou canst tell me the dream, that I saw, and the interpretation thereof?
\v 27 And Daniel answering before the king, said: The mystery, that the king demandeth, the wisemen, the Magicians, and the soothsayers, and the enchanters cannot declare unto the king. \f + \fr 2:27 \ft By shewing the King's former cogitation before his dream, he gave great assurance of the true spirit of prophecy, that the King might securely believe the interpretation of the dream.\f*
\v 28 But there is a God in heaven that revealeth mysteries, who hath shewed unto thee, king Nabuchodonosor, what things are to come in the later times. Thy dream, and the visions of thy head in thy bed, are these.
\v 29 Thou o king beganst to think in thy bed, what should be hereafter: and he that revealeth mysteries, shewed thee what things are to come. \f + \fr 2:29 \ft The four Kingdom of the Chaldees, Persians, Grecians, and Romans, signified by the four parts of this statua,\f*
\v 30 To me also not in the wisdom, that is in me more than in all men alive, is this sacrament revealed: but that the interpretation might be made manifest to the king, and thou mightest know the cogitations of thy mind.
\v 31 Thou o king didst see, and behold as it were one great statua: that statua, great and high of stature stood over against thee, and the sight thereof was terrible. \f + \fr 2:31 \ft consisting of diverse metals or matter, did succeed in order of time:\f*
\v 32 The head of this statua was of the best gold, but the breast and the arms of silver, moreover the belly, and the thighs of brass: \f + \fr 2:32 \ft not each one meaner, or baser than the former, as gold is best, & iron & earth the worst, for the last rather excelled the former; but when this vision appeared the kingdom of the Chaldees was the greatest, and most excellent & that being destroyed the Medes & Persians became greater than it had been: again the Grecians under Alexander became far greater than any before, and finally the Roman greatest of all, till Christ's kingdom, his Church was spread over the whole world.\f*
\v 33 and the legs of iron, of the feet a certain part was of iron, and a certain of earth.
\v 34 Thou sawest so, till a stone was cut out of a mountain without hands: and it struck the statua on the iron, & earthen feet thereof, & brake them in pieces.
\v 35 Then were the iron, the clay, the brass, the silver, and gold broken together, and brought as it were into the dust of a summer's floor, that are taken violently with the wind: and there was no place found for them: but the stone that struck the statua, was made a great mountain, and it filled all the earth.
\v 36 This is the dream: the interpretation also thereof we will tell before thee, o king.
\v 37 Thou art the king of kings: and the God of heaven hath given thee kingdom, and strength, and empire, and glory:
\v 38 and all things, wherein the children of men, and the beasts of the field do inhabit, the fowls also of the heaven he hath given in thy hand, and under thy dominion he hath appointed all things: thou therefore art the golden head.
\v 39 And after thee shall rise up another kingdom less than thou of silver: and another third kingdom of brass, which shall rule over all the world.
\v 40 And the fourth kingdom shall be as it were iron. As iron breaketh into pieces, & tameth all things, so shall that break, and destroy all these.
\v 41 Moreover because thou sawest part of the feet, and of the toes of the potter's clay, and part of iron: the kingdom shall be divided, which notwithstanding shall rise of the ground of iron, according as thou sawest the iron mingled with the earth of clay.
\v 42 And the toes in part of iron, and in part of earth: in part the kingdom shall be whole, and in part broken.
\v 43 And that thou sawest the iron mingled with the earth of clay, they shall be mingled indeed together with man's seed, but they shall not stick fast one to another, as iron cannot be mingled with earth.
\v 44 But in the days of those kingdoms the God of Heaven will raise up a kingdom, that shall not be dissipated for ever, and his kingdom shall not be delivered to another people: and it shall break in pieces, and shall consume all these kingdoms: and itself shall stand for ever. \f + \fr 2:44 \ft The Church of Christ is the only kingdom that cannot be destroyed.\f*
\v 45 According as thou sawest, that the stone was cut out of the mountain without hands, and brake the earth in pieces, and the iron, and the brass, and the silver, and the gold, the great God hath shewed the king what things are to come hereafter. & the dream is true, & the interpretation thereof faithful.
\v 46 Then king Nabuchodonosor fell on his face, & adored Daniel, & commanded to sacrifice to him hosts & incense. \f + \fr 2:46 \ft He thought Daniel to be a little god, subject to the great God. v. 47.\f*
\v 47 The king therefore speaking said to Daniel: In very deed your God is the God of gods, and Lord of kings, and he that revealeth mysteries: because thou couldst open this sacrament. \f + \fr 2:47 \ft Notwithstanding this confession, shortly after he erected an idol to represent his own greatness, and to be adored therein.\f* \f + \fr 2:47 \ft * mystery.\f*
\v 48 Then the king advanced Daniel on high, & he gave him many gifts, and great: and he made him prince over all the provinces of Babylon: and chief of the magistrates, over all the wisemen of Babylon.
\v 49 And Daniel requested of the king, and he appointed over the works of the province of Babylon, Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago: but Daniel himself was in the doors of the king.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 Nabuchodonosor the king made a statua of gold in height of sixty cubits, in breadth of six cubits, and he set it in the field of Dura of the province of Babylon. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft This huge statua of ninety foot in height and nine in breadth contained a great mass of gold. Which the King made to shew his riches, to terrify his enemies, & to represent himself, that he might be adored therein as a god. S. Ierom.\f*
\v 2 Therefore Nabuchodonosor the king sent to call together the nobles, the magistrates, and judges, dukes, and tyrants, and rulers, and all the princes of the countries, that they should come together to the dedication of the statua, which Nabuchodonosor the king had erected.
\v 3 Then were the nobles gathered together, the magistrates, and judges, the dukes, and tyrants, & the great men that were placed in regiments, and all the princes of the countries, to come together to the dedication of the statua, which Nabuchodonosor the king had erected. And they stood in the sight of the statua, which Nabuchodonosor the king had set up.
\v 4 And the crier cried mightily: To you peoples, and tribes, and tongues it is said:
\v 5 In the hour that you shall hear the sound of the trumpet, & pipe, and harp, of the dulcimer, and psalter, and symphony, & all kind of musical instruments: falling adore ye the golden statua, which Nabuchodonosor the king hath set up.
\v 6 But if any man shall not adore prostrate, he shall the self same hour be cast into a furnace of burning fire. \f + \fr 3:6 \ft Practice of this idolatry consisted in falling prostrate on the ground before the statua; sometimes it consisteth in offering incense to idols; and the like; Now in England personal presence at heretical service or sermon is a distinctive sign of conformity to the protestants' pretended religion; because such presence is there exacted for this purpose.\f*
\v 7 After this therefore forthwith as all the peoples heard the sound of the trumpet, the pipe, & harp, of the dulcimer, and psalter, of the symphony, and of all kind of musical instruments: all the peoples, tribes, and tongues falling adored the golden statua, which Nabuchodonosor the king had set up.
\v 8 And forthwith in the very same time men of Chaldee coming accused the Jews,
\v 9 and said to Nabuchodonosor the king: King for ever live:
\v 10 thou, o king hast made a decree, that every man which shall hear the sound of the trumpet, of the pipe, and harp, of the dulcimer, and psalter, of the symphony, and of all kind of musical instruments, prostrate himself, and adore the golden statua:
\v 11 and if any man do not prostrate on the ground adore, that he be cast into a furnace of burning fire.
\v 12 There are therefore men of Jewry, whom thou didst appoint over the works of the country of Babylon, Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago: these men, o king, have contemned thy decree: thy gods they worship not, and the golden statua, which thou hast erected, they adore not.
\v 13 Then Nabuchodonosor in fury, and in wrath commanded, that Sidrach, Misach, & Abdenago should be brought: who immediately were brought before the king.
\v 14 And Nabuchodonosor the king pronouncing, said to them: Indeed Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, do not you worship my gods, & the golden statua that I have set up do not you adore?
\v 15 Now therefore if you be ready, in what hour soever you shall hear the sound of the trumpet, the pipe, the harp, of the dulcimer, and psalter, and symphony, and of all kind of musical instruments, prostrate yourselves, & adore the statua which I have made: but if you adore not, the self same hour you shall be cast into the furnace of burning fire: and what God is there that shall deliver you out of my hand?
\v 16 Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago answering said to king Nabuchodonosor: We must not answer thee concerning this thing.
\v 17 For behold our God, whom we worship, can save us from the furnace of burning fire, and out of thy hands, o king, deliver us. \f + \fr 3:17 \ft By this most modest & confident answer they professed their assured faith of God's omnipotent power, not knowing whether it was his divine will to deliver them from the fire or no: resolving to suffer with patience whatsoever he would permit to fall unto them.\f*
\v 18 But if he will not, be it known to thee, o king, that we worship not thy gods, & the golden statua, which thou hast erected, we adore not.
\v 19 Then was Nabuchodonosor replenished with fury: and the look of his face was altered upon Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, and he commanded that the furnace should be heated seven times more, than it had been accustomed to be heated.
\v 20 And commanded the strongest men of his host, to bind the feet of Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, and to cast them into the furnace of burning fire.
\v 21 And forthwith those men being bound with their breeches, and head attire, and shoes, and garments were cast into the furnace of burning fire. \f + \fr 3:21 \ft * or caps.\f*
\v 22 For the commandment of the king did urge, and the furnace was heated exceedingly. Moreover the flame of the fire slew those men, that had cast in Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago.
\v 23 But these three men, that is, Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago fell in the midst of the furnace of burning fire, bound together. \f + \fr 3:23 \ft Though these parcels were not in the Hebrew in S. Jerome's time, yet either had been in the Hebrew or Chaldee, or at least were Canonical scriptures; as we have proved in the argument of this book.\f*
\v 24 And they walked in the midst of the flame praising God, and blessing our Lord.
\v 25 And Azarias standing prayed thus, and opening his mouth in the midst of the fire, he said:
\v 26 Blessed art thou o Lord the God of our fathers, and laudable, and glorious is thy name for ever:
\v 27 because thou art just in all things, which thou hast done to us, and all thy works are true, and thy ways right, and all thy judgements true.
\v 28 For thou hast done true judgements according to all things, that thou hast brought upon us, and upon the holy city of our fathers Jerusalem: because in truth, & in judgement thou hast brought in all these things for our sins.
\v 29 For we have sinned, and done unjustly revolting from thee: and we have offended in all things;
\v 30 and thy precepts we have not heard, nor observed, nor done as thou hadst commanded us, that it might be well with us.
\v 31 All things therefore that thou hast brought in upon us, and all things that thou hast done to us, thou hast done with true judgement:
\v 32 and thou hast delivered us into the hands of our enemies unjust, & most wicked, & prevaricators, & to an unjust king and most wicked above all the earth.
\v 33 And now we cannot open the mouth: we are become a confusion, and reproach to thy servants, & to them that worship thee.
\v 34 Deliver us not for ever, we beseech thee, for thy name sake, and dissipate not thy testament:
\v 35 neither take thou away thy mercy from us, for Abraham thy beloved, and Isaac thy servant, and Israel thy holy one: \f + \fr 3:35 \ft In the very same manner Moyses prayed, & pacified God's wrath. Exo. 32.\f*
\v 36 to whom thou hast spoken, promising that thou wouldest multiply their seed as the stars of heaven, and as the sand that is in the sea shore.
\v 37 Because o Lord we are diminished more than all nations, and are abased in all the earth this day for our sins.
\v 38 And there is not at this time prince, & duke, and prophet, nor holocaust, nor sacrifice, nor oblation, nor incense, nor place of first fruits before thee, \f + \fr 3:38 \ft Sedecias being dead, and Ioachin kept in prison, there was none in state of a King amongst the Jews: neither was there at this time any Prophet in all Jewry: for Daniel himself and Ezechiel were in Babylon: and Jeremy was either dead or in Ægypt.\f*
\v 39 that we may find thy mercy: but in contrite mind, & spirit of humility let us be received.
\v 40 As in holocaust of rams, and bulls, and as in thousands of fat lambs: so let our sacrifice be made in thy sight this day, that it may please thee: because there is no confusion to them that trust in thee.
\v 41 And now we follow thee in all our heart, and fear thee, and seek thy face.
\v 42 Confound us not, but do with us according to thy meekness, and according to the multitude of thy mercy.
\v 43 And deliver us in thy marvels, and give glory to thy name o Lord:
\v 44 and let all be confounded that shew evils to thy servants, let them be confounded in all thy might, and let their strength be broken:
\v 45 and let them know that thou art the Lord, the only God, and glorious over the round world.
\v 46 And the king's servants that had cast them in, ceased not to heat the furnace, with Naphtha, and tow, and pitch, and dry sticks, \f + \fr 3:46 \ft chalky, clay, or lime.\f*
\v 47 and the flame mounted out above the furnace nine and forty cubits:
\v 48 and it brake forth, and burnt them whom it found by the furnace, of the Chaldees.
\v 49 But the Angel of our Lord descended with Azarias, and his fellows into the furnace: and he shook the flame of the fire out of the furnace,
\v 50 and made the midst of the furnace as a wind of dew blowing, and the fire touched them not at all, nor pained them, nor did them any grievance.
\v 51 Then these three as out of one mouth praised, and glorified, and blessed God in the furnace, saying:
\v 52 Blessed art thou o Lord the God of our fathers: and laudable, and glorious, and superexalted for ever: and blessed is the holy name of thy glory: and laudable, and superexalted in all ages.
\v 53 Blessed art thou in the holy temple of thy glory: & passing laudable, and passing glorious for ever.
\v 54 Blessed art thou in the throne of thy kingdom, and passing laudable, and superexalted for ever.
\v 55 Blessed art thou, that beholdest the depths, and sittest upon the Cherubs: and laudable, and superexalted for ever.
\v 56 Blessed art thou in the firmament of heaven: and laudable and glorious for ever.
\v 57 All works of our Lord bless ye our Lord, praise and superexalt him for ever. \f + \fr 3:57 \ft Holy Angels do incessantly praise God, and therefore need not to be invited thereto; sensible creatures do not properly praise God, because they have not understanding nor will: but the meaning of this invitation is, to congratulate that Angels do always without intermission praise God, & to exhort all men in consideration of all God's works, spiritual and corporal, to praise him as most worthy to be praised by all men.\f*
\v 58 Bless our Lord ye Angels of our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 59 Ye heavens bless our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 60 All waters that are above the heavens, bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 61 Bless our Lord all ye powers of our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 62 Sun and moon bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 63 Stars of heavens bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 64 Every shower, & dew bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 65 All spirits of God bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 66 Fire and heat bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 67 Cold and heat bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 68 Dews and hoar frost bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 69 Frost and cold bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 70 Ice and snows bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 71 Nights and days bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 72 Light and darkness bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever. \f + \fr 3:72 \ft Privations of things have also their decent course in the universal state of creatures: Darkness praiseth God, that is, bringeth forth praise in the hearts of considerative men. S. Aug. li. de natura boni c. 16.\f*
\v 73 Lightnings and clouds bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 74 Let the earth bless our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 75 Mountains and little hills bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 76 All things that spring in the earth bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 77 Bless our Lord ye fountains: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 78 Seas and rivers bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 79 Whales, and all things that move in the waters, bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 80 Bless our Lord all ye fowls of heaven: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 81 All beasts and cattle bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 82 Sons of men bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 83 Let Israel bless our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 84 Priests of our Lord bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 85 Servants of our Lord bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 86 Spirits and souls of the just bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 87 Holy and humble of heart bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever.
\v 88 Ananias, Azarias, and Misael, bless ye our Lord: praise and superexalt him for ever. Because he hath delivered us from hell, and saved us out of the hand of death, and delivered us out of the midst of the burning flame, and out of the midst of the fire hath he rid us.
\v 89 Confess ye to our Lord, because he is good: because his mercy is for ever.
\v 90 All religious bless ye our Lord the God of gods: praise and confess ye to him, because his mercy is unto all worlds. \f + \fr 3:90 \ft S. Jerome's words.\f*
\v 91 Then Nabuchodonosor the king was astonished, and he arose hastily, & said to his nobles: Did we not cast three men fettered into the midst of the fire? Who answering the king, said: It is true o king. \f + \fr 3:91 \ft The fire burned their bands, but not their garments nor bodies: so God useth the service of his creatures to give comfort to his servants & not torment. S. Greg. li. 3. c. 18. dialo. Where he writeth the like miracle, when the Goths would have burned S. Benedict.\f*
\v 92 He answered, and said: Behold I see four men loose, and walking in the midst of the fire, and there is no corruption in them, & the form of the fourth is like to the son of God. \f + \fr 3:92 \ft This fourth was the Angel that averted the force of the fire from them. v. 49. & 95.\f*
\v 93 Then came Nabuchodonosor to the door of the furnace of burning fire, and said: Sidrach, Misach, & Abdenago, servants of the high God, go ye forth, and come. And forthwith Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago went out of the midst of the fire.
\v 94 And the nobles, and the magistrates, and judges, and the potentates of the king being gathered together, beheld those men, that the fire had no power on their bodies, & not a hair of their head was singed, yea their breeches were not altered, & the scent of the fire had not passed by them.
\v 95 And Nabuchodonosor breaking forth, said: Blessed be the God of them, to wit, of Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, who hath sent his Angel, and hath delivered his servants that believed in him: and they changed the king's word, & delivered their bodies that they might not serve, and might not adore any god, except their own God.
\v 96 By me therefore this decree is made, that every people, tribe, and tongue, whatsoever shall speak blasphemy against the God of Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago, he perish, and his house be wasted: for there is none other God, that can so save.
\v 97 Then did the king promote Sidrach, Misach, and Abdenago in the province of Babylon. \f + \fr 3:97 \ft They were not only restored to their former authority, as prefects over the works. ch. 2. v. 49. but were also more advanced, as this place insinuateth.\f*
\v 98 Nabuchodonosor the king, to all peoples, nations, and tongues, that dwell in the whole earth, peace be multiplied unto you.
\v 99 The high God hath wrought signs and marvelous things with me. It hath pleased me therefore to publish
\v 100 his signs, because they are great: and his marvels, because they are strong: and his kingdom an everlasting kingdom, & his power in generation and to generation.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 I Nabuchodonosor, was quiet in my house, and flourishing in my palace. \f + \fr 4:1 \ft It seemeth that Daniel inserted this particular history as the King in his own person & words reported it after his restoration. It is also probable that the King had this dream about the 34. year of his reign. For he reigning in all 43. years, lived seven years among beasts: into which state he fell one year after this dream, v. 26. and lived about a year more or less after his restoration.\f*
\v 2 Isaw a dream that made me sore afraid: and my cogitations in my bed, and the visions of my head disturbed me.
\v 3 And by me there was a decree set forth, that all the wisemen of Babylon should be brought into my sight, and that they should shew me the solution of the dream.
\v 4 Then came in the soothsayers, magicians, Chaldees, and diviners, and I told the dream in their sight: & the solution thereof they shewed me not:
\v 5 till their colleague Daniel came into my sight, whose name is Baltassar, according to the name of my god, who hath the spirit of the holy gods in himself: and I told the dream before him.
\v 6 Baltassar prince of the soothsayers, because I know that thou hast the spirit of the holy gods in thee, and no secret is impossible to thee: tell thou the visions of my dreams, which I have seen, and the solution of them.
\v 7 The vision of my head in my bed, I saw, and behold a tree in the midst of the earth, and the height thereof exceeding.
\v 8 Agreat tree, and strong: and the height thereof touching the heaven: the sight thereof was even to the ends of all the earth.
\v 9 The leaves thereof most fair, and the fruit thereof exceeding much: and the food of all things in it: under it dwelt cattle, and beasts, and in the boughs thereof conversed the fowls of heaven: and of it all flesh did eat.
\v 10 Isaw in the vision of my head upon my bed, & behold a watchman, and an holy one descended from heaven.
\v 11 He cried mightily, and thus he said: Cut ye down the tree, & chop off the boughs thereof: shake off the leaves thereof, and scatter the fruits thereof: let the beasts fly that are under it, and the fowls from the boughs thereof.
\v 12 But yet leave the spring of the roots thereof in the earth, and let it be tied with iron, and brazen band among the grass, that is without, and let it be dipped with the dew of heaven, and with wild beasts his portion in the grass of the earth.
\v 13 Let his heart be changed from human, & let the heart of a wild beast be given him: and let seven times be changed over him. \f + \fr 4:13 \ft Seven times signify seven years, because all ordinary varieties of times are in one year.\f*
\v 14 In the sentence of the watchman is the decree, and the word of saints, and the petition, till the living know, that the high one ruleth in the kingdom of men; and to whom soever it shall please him, he will give it, & the basest man he will appoint over it.
\v 15 This dream saw I Nabuchodonosor the king: thou therefore o Baltassar tell the interpretation quickly: because all the wisemen of my kingdom cannot declare the solution unto me: but thou canst, because the spirit of holy gods is in thee.
\v 16 Then Daniel, whose name was Baltassar, began secretly to think within himself as it were for one hour: & his cogitations troubled him. But the king answering said: Baltassar, let not the dream and the interpretation thereof trouble thee. Baltassar answered, and said: My lord, the dream be to them, that hate thee, and the interpretation thereof be thine enemies. \f + \fr 4:16 \ft No marvel that the prophet was troubled in mind being loath to declare the calamity which should fall unto the king, and yet must needs utter the truth. And therefore with mild words, wishing the King might escape the evil, which was decreed against him, he maketh his entrance to the true interpretation of the dream.\f*
\v 17 The tree which thou sawest high and strong, whose height reacheth to heaven, and the sight thereof into all the earth:
\v 18 and the bough thereof most fair, and the fruit thereof exceeding much, and the food of things in it, under it the beasts of the field inhabiting, & in the boughs thereof the fowls of heaven abiding:
\v 19 It is thou king, which art magnified, & become mighty: & thy greatness hath grown, and is come even to heaven, and thy power unto the ends of the earth.
\v 20 But in that the king saw a watchman, and an holy one descend from heaven, and say: Cut ye down the tree, and dissipate it, but leave the spring of the roots thereof in the earth, and let it be bound with iron and brass among the grass without, and let it be sprinkled with the dew of heaven, and let his fodder be with the wild beasts, till seven times be changed over him.
\v 21 This is the interpretation of the sentence of the Highest, which is come upon my lord the king.
\v 22 They shall cast thee out from men, and with beasts and wild beasts shall thy habitation be, and grass thou shalt eat as an ox, & with the dew of heaven thou shalt be wet: seven times also shall be changed over thee, till thou know that the High one ruleth over the kingdoms of men, and giveth it to whomsoever he will.
\v 23 But whereas he commanded, that the spring of the roots thereof, that is, of the tree, should be left: thy kingdom shall remain to thee after thou shalt have known that power is heavenly.
\v 24 Wherefore o king let me counsel thee, and redeem thou thy sins with alms, & thine iniquities with the mercies of the poor: perhaps he will forgive thine offences. \f + \fr 4:24 \ft God's threats being conditional that if sinners truly repent he will pardon all, or part of the punishment, the prophet proposeth the most sovereign remedy of alms deeds that by works of mercy this sinful king, or any other sinner may procure the mercy of God. As indeed this king found mercy after some punishment: the prophet proposeth the sovereign remedy of alms deeds, that by works of mercy, he might procure God's mercy.\f*
\v 25 All these things came upon Nabuchodonosor the king.
\v 26 After the end of twelve months he walked in the palace of Babylon.
\v 27 And the king answered, & said: Is not this Babylon the great city, which I have built to be the house of the kingdom, in the strength of my power, and in the glory of my beauty?
\v 28 And when the word was yet in the king's mouth, a voice came down from heaven: To thee it is said Nabuchodonosor: Thy kingdom shall pass from thee,
\v 29 and from men they shall cast thee out, and with beasts and wild beasts shall thy habitation be: grass as an ox shalt thou eat, and seven times shall be changed over thee till thou know that the High one ruleth in the kingdom of men, & to whom soever he will, he giveth it.
\v 30 The self same hour was the word accomplished upon Nabuchodonosor, and he was cast away from among men, & as an ox did he eat grass, and with the dew of heaven his body was imbrued: till his hairs grew into the similitude of eagles', & his nails as it were of birds'.
\v 31 Therefore after the end of the days, I Nabuchodonosor lifted up mine eyes to heaven, and my sense was restored to me: and I blessed the Highest, and praised him that liveth for ever, and glorified him: because his power is an everlasting power, and his kingdom in generation and generation.
\v 32 And all the inhabitants of the earth with him are reputed for nothing: for he doth according to his will, as well in the powers of heaven, as in the inhabitants of the earth: & there is none that can resist his hand, and say to him: Why didst thou it?
\v 33 In the very same time did my sense return to me, & I came to the honour, and beauty of my kingdom: and my figure returned to me: and my nobles, & my magistrates sought for me, and I was restored in my kingdom: and more ample magnificence was added to me. \f + \fr 4:33 \ft Being restored to his wits he went up right, cut his hair\f*
\v 34 Now therefore I Nabuchodonosor praise, and magnify, and glorify the King of heaven: because all his works are true, and his ways judgements, and them that walk in pride he can humble.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 \sc Baltassar\sc* the king made a great feast to his nobles a thousand: and every one drank according to his age. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft The ruin of this Baltassar happened in the 17. and last year of his reign: when Daniel was near an hundred years.\f*
\v 2 He commanded therefore now being drunk that the vessels of gold & silver, should be brought, which Nabuchodonosor his father had carried away out of the temple, that was in Jerusalem, that the king, and his Nobles might drink in them, and his wives, and concubines.
\v 3 Then were the golden and silver vessels brought, which he had carried away out of the temple, that was in Jerusalem: and the king and his nobles drank in them, his wives and concubines.
\v 4 They drank wine, and praised their gods of gold, and of silver, of brass, of iron, and of wood, and of stone.
\v 5 In the very same hour there appeared fingers, as it were of the hand of a man, writing over against the candlestick in the utter part of the wall of the king's palace: and the king beheld the joints of the hand that wrote.
\v 6 Then was the king's face changed, and his cogitations troubled him: and the junctures of his reins were loosed, and his knees were strucken one against the other.
\v 7 The king therefore cried out mightily that they should bring in the magicians, Chaldees, and soothsayers. And the king speaking said to the wisemen of Babylon: Whosoever shall read this writing, and shall make the interpretation thereof manifest unto me, shall be clothed with purple, and shall have a golden chain on his neck, & shall be the third in my kingdom.
\v 8 Then all the king's wisemen going in could not neither read the writing, nor declare the interpretation to the king.
\v 9 Wherewith king Baltassar was much troubled, and his countenance was changed: yea and his nobles were troubled.
\v 10 And the queen for the thing that had happened to the king, and his nobles, entered into the house of the feast: and speaking she said: King for ever live: let not thy cogitations trouble thee, neither let thy face be changed. \f + \fr 5:10 \ft * the King's mother v. 11.\f*
\v 11 There is a man in thy kingdom, that hath the spirit of the holy gods in him: and in the days of thy father knowledge and wisdom were found in him: for king Nabuchodonosor also thy father appointed him prince of the magicians, enchanters, Chaldees and soothsayers, thy father, I say o king: \f + \fr 5:11 \ft All progenitors are commonly called the fathers of their offspring: so Nabuchodonosor is called the father of Baltasar, being his grand father: as may be gathered, Ier. 27. v. 7. where is prophesied that Nabuchodonosor & his son, and son's son should reign over many nations.\f*
\v 12 Because more ample spirit, and prudence, and understanding, & interpretation of dreams, and shewing of secrets, and solution of things bound were found in him, that is, in Daniel: to whom the king gave the name Baltassar. Now therefore let Daniel be called, and he will tell the interpretation.
\v 13 Daniel therefore was brought in before the king. To whom the king speaking, said: Art thou Daniel of the children of the captivity of Juda, whom my father the king brought out of Jewry?
\v 14 I have heard of thee, that thou hast the spirit of the gods, and more ample knowledge, and understanding, and wisdom are found in thee.
\v 15 And now there have come into my sight the wise magicians, that they might read this writing, and might shew me the interpretation thereof: and they could not declare me the sense of this word. \f + \fr 5:15 \ft * thing written.\f*
\v 16 Moreover I have heard of thee, that thou canst interpret obscure things, and resolve things bound: if therefore thou be able to read the writing, & to shew me the interpretation thereof, thou shalt be clothed with purple, and shalt have a chain of gold about thy neck, & shalt be the third prince in my kingdom.
\v 17 To which things Daniel answering, said before the king: Thy rewards be they unto thee, and the gifts of thy house give to another: but the writing will I read thee, o king, and the interpretation thereof will I shew to thee.
\v 18 O king, God the most high gave to Nabuchodonosor thy father kingdom and magnificence, glory and honour.
\v 19 And for the magnificence, which he gave to him, all peoples, tribes, and tongues trembled, and feared him: whom he would he killed: and whom he would, he struck: and whom he would he exalted: and whom he would, he humbled.
\v 20 But when his heart was elevated, and his spirit obstinately set to pride, he was deposed from the throne of his kingdom, and his glory was taken away.
\v 21 And he was cast out from the sons of men, yea and his heart was set with the beasts, and with the wild asses was his habitation: grass also he did eat as an ox, and with the dew of heaven his body was imbrued: till he knew that the Highest had power in the kingdom of men, and whomsoever it shall please him he will raise up over it. \f + \fr 5:21 \ft His imagination that he was a beast made him forsake the company of men, and to dwell amongst wild beasts. ch. 4.\f*
\v 22 Thou also his son Baltassar, hast not humbled thy heart, whereas thou knowest all these things:
\v 23 but against the dominator of heaven thou wast elevated: and the vessels of his house have been brought before thee: and thou, and thy nobles, and thy wives, and thy concubines have drunk wine in them: the gods also of silver, and of gold, and of brass, of iron, and of wood, and of stone that see not, nor hear, nor feel, thou hast praised: moreover the God, that hath thy breath in his hand, and all thy ways, thou hast not glorified.
\v 24 Therefore from him is the joint of the hand sent, which hath written this that is drawn.
\v 25 And this is the writing which is ordered: \sc Mane, Thecel, Phares\sc*.
\v 26 And this the interpretation of the word. \sc Mane\sc*: God hath numbered thy kingdom, and hath finished it.
\v 27 \sc Thecel\sc*: thou art weighed in the balance, and art found having less.
\v 28 \sc Phares\sc*: thy kingdom is divided, and is given to the Medes, and Persians.
\v 29 Then the king commanding Daniel was clothed with purple, and a chain of gold was put about his neck: & it was proclaimed of him that he had power the third in the kingdom.
\v 30 The same night was Baltassar the king of Chaldee slain. \f + \fr 5:30 \ft The Medes being at this time in the siege of Babylon, took their opportunity to assault it this night, when the King and most part of the city were drunk.\f*
\v 31 And Darius the Mede succeeded into the kingdom, being three score and two years old.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 IT pleased Darius, and he appointed over the kingdom governers an hundred twenty to be in all his kingdom. \f + \fr 6:1 \ft Darius (King of Medes now also of Chaldees) otherwise called Astyages (ch. 13. v. 65.) reigned but one year, and so Cyrus succeeded.\f*
\v 2 And over them three princes, of whom Daniel was one: that the governers might render account to them, & the king might sustain no trouble.
\v 3 Daniel therefore passed all the princes, and governers: because there was the spirit of God more ample in him.
\v 4 Moreover the king thought to appoint him over all the kingdom, whereupon the princes, & the governers sought to find occasion against Daniel on the behalf of the king: and they could find no cause, nor suspicion, because he was faithful, and no fault, nor suspicion was found in him.
\v 5 Those men therefore said: We shall not find against this same Daniel any occasion, unless perhaps in the law of his God. \f + \fr 6:5 \ft An old and continual malignant practice, to call religion treason: And for that purpose to procure laws or statutes to be enacted.\f*
\v 6 Then the princes, and the governers by surreption suggested to the king, and spake thus unto him: King Darius, for ever live:
\v 7 All the princes of the kingdom, the magistrates, and governers, the senators and judges have taken counsel, that there go forth an imperial decree, and an edict: That every one, which shall ask any petition of whatsoever god, or man, until thirty days, but of thee o king, he be cast into the lake of lions.
\v 8 Now therefore o king confirm the sentence, and write the decree: that it may not be changed, which is decreed by the Medes and the Persians, nor be lawful for any man to transgress it.
\v 9 Moreover king Darius put forth the edict, and decreed it.
\v 10 Which when Daniel had perceived, that is to say, the law determined, he went into his house: and the windows being opened in his upper chamber, three times in a day toward Jerusalem bowed he his knees, and adored, and confessed before his God, as also he had accustomed to do before. \f + \fr 6:10 \ft It is not probable that Daniel opened the windows of purpose, that he might be seen to pray: for so he should have undiscreetly contemned the King, and provoked the infidels to persecute him; but having accustomed to open the windows of his upper chamber, which gave prospect towards Jerusalem, according to Salomon's prayer 3. Reg. 8. v. 47. & 48. he observed the same custom still: & was not seen publicly of many, but his enemies searching curiously (v. 11.) found him praying, and accused him of breaking the King's Edict.\f*
\v 11 Those men therefore searching curiously, found Daniel praying, and beseeching his God.
\v 12 And coming they spake to the king upon the edict: O king, hast thou not decreed, that every man which should ask any of the gods, & men until thirty days, but thyself o king, he should be cast into the lake of lions? To whom the king answering, said: The word is true according to the decree of the Medes, and Persians, which it is not lawful to transgress.
\v 13 Then they answering said before the king: Daniel of the children of the captivity of Juda, hath not cared for thy law, and for the edict, that thou madest: but three times in a day he prayeth with his prayer.
\v 14 Which word when the king had heard, he was strucken very sad: and for Daniel he set his heart to deliver him, and even until sun set he laboured to deliver him.
\v 15 But those men perceiving the king said to him: know thou o king, that the law of Medes and Persians is, that every decree, which the king hath determined, is not lawful to be changed.
\v 16 Then the king commanded, and they brought Daniel, and cast him into the lake of lions. And the king said to Daniel: Thy God, whom thou doest worship always, he will deliver thee.
\v 17 And there was a stone brought, and laid upon the mouth of the lake: which the king sealed with his ring, and with the ring of his nobles, that nothing should be done against Daniel.
\v 18 And the king went into his house, and slept unsupped, and meats were not brought before him, moreover also sleep departed from him.
\v 19 Then the king rising in the very first break of day, went in haste to the lake of the lions:
\v 20 and approaching to the lake, cried on Daniel with a weeping voice, and spake unto him: Daniel servant of the living God, thy God whom thou servest always, hath he been able thinkest thou, to deliver thee from the lions?
\v 21 And Daniel answering the king said: King for ever live.
\v 22 My God hath sent his Angel, and hath shut up the mouths of the lions, and they have not hurt me: because before him justice hath been found in me: yea and before thee, o king, I have done no offence. \f + \fr 6:22 \ft To this miracle wrought by the power of God in defence, and for the merits of this holy Prophet, S. Paul alludeth, Heb. 11. v. 33.\f*
\v 23 Then was the king exceeding glad upon him, & he commanded Daniel to be brought out of the lake: and Daniel was brought out of the lake, and no hurt was found in him, because he believed his God.
\v 24 And by the king's commandment, those men were brought that had accused Daniel: and they were cast into the lake of the lions, themselves, and their children, and their wives: and they came not to the pavement of the lake, till the lions caught them, & brake all their bones in pieces. \f + \fr 6:24 \ft The law of like-punishment is so agreeable to the law of nature, that this Pagan King punished Daniel's accusers, when it appeared to him, that Daniel had not committed treason, but only used his religion and devotion.\f*
\v 25 Then Darius the king wrote to all peoples, tribes, and tongues dwelling in the whole earth: \sc Peace\sc* be multiplied unto you.
\v 26 By me a decree is made, that in all mine empire, and my kingdom they dread and fear the God of Daniel. for he is the living and eternal God for ever: and his kingdom shall not be dissipated, & his power even for ever.
\v 27 He is the deliverer, and saviour, doing sign, & marvels in heaven, and in earth: who hath delivered Daniel out of the lake of the lions.
\v 28 Moreover Daniel continued unto the kingdom of Darius, and the kingdom of Cyrus the Persian.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 IN the first year of Baltassar the king of Babylon, Daniel saw a dream: & the vision of his head in his bed: and writing the dream, he comprehended it in a short speech: and in sum comprising it, he said: \f + \fr 7:1 \ft In order of time these two visions were before the histories written in the two precedent chapters.\f*
\v 2 Isaw in my vision by night, and behold the four winds of heaven fought in the great sea. \f + \fr 7:2 \ft Four winds may signify the great tumults which happen in the beginning of monarchies by wars and bloodshed of much people.\f*
\v 3 And four great beasts came up, out of the sea diverse one from another. \f + \fr 7:3 \ft Four beasts do signify the four Monarchies of the Chaldees, Medes and Persians, the Grecians, & the Romans: as was also signified before in Nabuchodonosor's dream. ch. 2.\f*
\v 4 The first as it were a lioness, & she had the wings of an eagle: I beheld till her wings were plucked off, and she was lifted up from the earth, & she stood upon the feet as a man, & the heart of a man was given to her. \f + \fr 7:4 \ft Alioness's cruelty, and the pride of an eagle do resemble the Chaldee's monarchy.\f*
\v 5 And behold another beast like a bear stood aside: and there were three rews in the mouth thereof, and in the teeth thereof, & thus they said to it: Arise, eat very much flesh. \f + \fr 7:5 \ft Abear of rude shape, & weak sight, content with little and base meat, represented the Medes & Persians.\f*
\v 6 After this I beheld, and lo another as it were a leopard, and it had wings as of a bird, four upon it, & there were four heads in the beast, and power was given to it. \f + \fr 7:6 \ft The leopard with wings and four heads, signified the speedy victories of the Grecians under Alexander in four quarters of the world: after his death divided into four Kingdoms.\f*
\v 7 After this I beheld in the vision of the night, and lo a fourth beast terrible and marvelous, and strong exceedingly, it had great iron teeth, eating and breaking, and treading the rest with her feet: and it was unlike to the other beasts, which I had seen before it, and it had ten horns. \f + \fr 7:7 \ft By the fourth beast without name is understood the incomparable power of the Romans: governing first by kingly authority; afterwards by Consuls; then joining to them Tribunes; sometimes Dictators; finally Emperial.\f*
\v 8 I considered the horns, and behold another little horn sprang out of the midst of them: and three of the first horns were plucked off at the presence thereof, and lo eyes as it were the eyes of a man were in this horn, & a mouth speaking great words. \f + \fr 7:8 \ft The little horn becoming so great and strong, as to overcome all the other, signifieth Antichrist; whose outrageous fury shall continue but a short time. v. 25.\f*
\v 9 I beheld till thrones were set, and the ancient of days sat: his vesture white as snow, and the hairs of his head as clean wool: his throne flames of fire: his wheels fire kindled. \f + \fr 7:9 \ft God the Father is called the Ancient of days, not as though one Person of the Blessed Trinity were more\f*
\v 10 Afire & swift stream came forth from his face: thousands of thousands ministered to him, & ten thousand hundred thousands assisted him: judgement sat, and the books were opened. \f + \fr 7:10 \ft By multiplication of these cardinal numbers, is signified the innumerable multitude of Angels: who do exceed all corporal creatures in number, as the celestial spheres exceed terrestrial bodies in greatness.\f* \f + \fr 7:10 \ft And the highest Hierarchy (who are Assistants) do far exceed the other Hierarchies in multitude. S. Dionys. c. 14. Hierar. coelest. S. Tho. p. 1. q. 112. a. 4.\f*
\v 11 I beheld because of the voice of the great words, which that horn spake: and I saw that the beast was slain, and the body thereof was perished, and was committed to the fire to be burnt.
\v 12 The power of the other beasts also was taken away: and times of life were appointed them until time, and time.
\v 13 I beheld therefore in the vision of the night, and lo with the clouds of heaven there came in, as it were the son of man, and he came even to the ancient of days: and in his sight they offered him. \f + \fr 7:13 \ft Our Saviour Christ is here clearly prophesied: by whose power Antichrist shall be utterly destroyed.\f*
\v 14 And he gave him power, and honour, and kingdom: and all peoples, tribes, & tongues shall serve him: his power, an eternal power, that shall not be taken away: and his kingdom, that shall not be corrupted.
\v 15 My spirit trembled, I Daniel was made sore afraid at these things, and the visions of my head troubled me.
\v 16 I came to one of the assistants, and I asked the truth of him concerning all these things, who told me the interpretation of the words, and taught me:
\v 17 These four great beasts, are four kingdoms, which shall rise up out of the earth.
\v 18 And they shall take the kingdom of the holy God most high: & they shall obtain the kingdom even to world, & world of worlds.
\v 19 After this I would diligently learn of the fourth beast, which was very unlike from all, and exceeding terrible: his teeth and claws of iron: he did eat, and break in pieces, & the rest he stamped with his feet:
\v 20 and of the ten horns that he had on his head: and of the other, that had grown up, before which the three horns fell: and of that horn, that had eyes, and the mouth speaking great words, and was greater than the rest.
\v 21 I beheld, and lo that horn made war against the saints, and prevailed over them,
\v 22 till the ancient of days came, & gave judgement to the saints on High, and the time came, and the saints obtained the kingdom.
\v 23 And thus he said: The fourth beast shall be the fourth kingdom in the earth, which shall be greater than all the kingdoms, and shall devour the whole earth, and shall conculcate, and break it in pieces.
\v 24 Moreover the ten horns of that same kingdom, shall be ten kings: and another shall rise up after them, and he shall be mightier than the former, and he shall bring down three kings.
\v 25 And he shall speak words against the High one, and shall destroy the saints of the Highest: and he shall think that he can change times, & laws, and they shall be delivered into his hand even to a time, & times, & half a time. \f + \fr 7:25 \ft ch. 12. v. 7. 11. & 12. Apoc. 11. v. 2. & 3. Apoc. 12. v. 6. & 14. & Apoc. 13. v. 5.\f*
\v 26 And judgement shall sit, that might may be taken away, and be broken, and perish even to the end.
\v 27 And kingdom, and power, and the greatness of the kingdom, that is under all the heaven, be given to the people of the saints of the Highest: whose kingdom is an everlasting kingdom, and all kings shall serve him, and shall obey him.
\v 28 Hitherto the end of the word, I Daniel was much troubled with my cogitations, and my face was changed in me: but the word I kept in my heart.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 IN the third year of the reign of Baltassar the king, a vision appeared to me.
\v 2 I Daniel saw in my vision, after that which I had seen in the beginning, when I was in Susis the castle, which is in the province of Ælam: and I saw in the vision, that I was over the gate Ulai. \f + \fr 8:2 \ft He insinuateth that this vision was in explication of some part of the former, which he had two years before. ch. 7. where four monarchies are mentioned: so here is foretold the great conflict between the Persians & Grecians, about 220 years after.\f* \f + \fr 8:2 \ft or river.\f*
\v 3 & I lifted up mine eyes, and saw: and behold one ram stood before the marish, having high horns, & one higher than another & growing under. \f + \fr 8:3 \ft The ram represented the King of Persians & Medes.\f*
\v 4 Afterward I saw the ram pushing with the horns against the West, & against the North, and against the South: and all beasts could not resist him, nor be delivered out of his hand: and he did according to his will, & was magnified.
\v 5 And I understood: and behold a buckgoat came from the West upon the face of the whole earth, & he touched not the ground. Moreover the buckgoat had a notable horn between his eyes: \f + \fr 8:5 \ft The goat signified Alexander the great:\f*
\v 6 And he came even to that ram with the horns, which I had seen standing before the gate, & he ran towards him in the violence of his strength.
\v 7 And when he had approached near the ram, he was wood against him, and struck the ram: and he brake his two horns, and the ram could not resist him: and when he had cast him on the ground, he trod him, and no man could deliver the ram out of his hand. \f + \fr 8:7 \ft breaking the two horns, that is conquering the two nations of Persians & Medes.\f*
\v 8 And the buckgoat became exceeding great: and when he was grown, the great horn was broken, and there rose up four horns under it by the four winds of heaven. \f + \fr 8:8 \ft King Alexander died when he was very young and strong not fully 33. years of age.\f* \f + \fr 8:8 \ft Four of his followers possessed every one a Kingdom of his Monarchy.\f*
\v 9 And out of one of them came forth one little horn: and it was made great against the South, and against the East, and against the strength. \f + \fr 8:9 \ft Antiochus Epiphanes persecuting the people of God, destroyed the sacrifice, polluted the temple, setting up the image of Jupiter Olympius.\f*
\v 10 And it was magnified even unto the strength of heaven: and it threw down of the strength, and of the stars, and trod them.
\v 11 And it was magnified even unto the prince of the strength: and from him it took the continual sacrifice, and threw down the place of his sanctification.
\v 12 And strength was given against the continual sacrifice because of sins: and truth shall be thrown prostrate on the ground, and he shall do, and shall prosper.
\v 13 And I heard one of the saints speaking, & one saint said to another, I know not to whom that spake: How long the vision, and the continual sacrifice, and the sin of the desolation that is made: and the sanctuary, and the strength shall be conculcate? \f + \fr 8:13 \ft One Angel demanded of another to know a thing to come.\f*
\v 14 And he said to him: Unto the evening & morning, two thousand three hundred: & the sanctuary shall be cleansed. \f + \fr 8:14 \ft 2300 evenings and mornings, that is, 2300 days, which make six years, & well near four months, the whole time from the beginning of Antiochus' persecution unto his death: for he began to persecute in the year 143. 1 Mac. 1. v. 21. & he died, an. 149. 1 Mac. 6. v. 16. within which time an. 148. the temple was purged 1. Mac. 4. v. 52.\f*
\v 15 And it came to pass when I Daniel saw the vision, and sought the understanding: behold there stood in my sight as it were the form of a man.
\v 16 And I heard the voice of a man between the banks of Ulai: and he cried, and said: Gabriel make this man understand the vision.
\v 17 And he came and stood near where I stood: and when he was come, trembling I fell on my face, & he said to me: Understand son of man, that in the time of the end the vision shall be accomplished. \f + \fr 8:17 \ft Ezechiel is very often called by the name of son of man, here also Daniel is so called by an Angel, as well to distinguish Angelical and human nature, as in honour of mankind, which Christ would assume: & therefore calleth himself by the very same title in the Gospel.\f*
\v 18 And when he spake to me I fell flat on the ground: and he touched me, and set me up in my standing,
\v 19 and said to me: I will shew thee what things are to come in the last of the malediction: because the time hath his end.
\v 20 The ram, which thou sawest have horns, is the king of the Medes and Persians.
\v 21 Moreover the buckgoat, is the king of the Græcians, and the great horn, that was between his eyes, the same is the first king.
\v 22 But whereas that being broken, there rose up four for it: four kings shall rise up of his nation, but not in his strength.
\v 23 And after their reign, when iniquities shall be increased, there shall arise a king impudent of face, and understanding propositions. \f + \fr 8:23 \ft Historically Antiochus; mystically Antichrist, as ch. 22. & Mat. 24.\f* \f + \fr 8:23 \ft * obscure speeches.\f*
\v 24 And his strength shall be made strong, but not in his own strength: and more than can be believed, shall he waste all things, and shall prosper, and do. And he shall kill the strong, and the people of the saints
\v 25 according to his will, and craft shall be directed in his hand: and he shall magnify his heart, and in the abundance of all things he shall murder very many: & against the prince of princes shall he arise, & without hand he shall be destroyed.
\v 26 & the vision of the evening and the morning, which hath been said, is true: thou therefore seal the vision, because it shall be after many days. \f + \fr 8:26 \ft So much as pertained to the profanation of the temple was fulfilled above 300. years after this prophecy: as the same is also a figure of Antichrist, it shall happen towards the end of this world. S. Greg. l. 30. c. 12. Moral.\f*
\v 27 And I Daniel languished, and was sick for certain days: and when I was risen up, I did the king's works, and was astonished at the vision, and there was none that could interpret it.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 IN the first year of Darius the son of Assuerus of the seed of the Medes, who reigned over the kingdom of the Chaldees: \f + \fr 9:1 \ft Assuerus, or Achasuerus, not a proper name signifieth a great Prince, or head of people.\f*
\v 2 the first year of his kingdom, I Daniel understood in books the number of years, whereof the word of our Lord was made to Jeremie the prophet, that seventy years should be accomplished of the desolation of Jerusalem. \f + \fr 9:2 \ft Darius had reigned in Persia before this time, but this was the first year of his reign over the Chaldees, and also the last, neither did he reign a full year: for Cyrus reigned some part of the seventieth year of the Jews' captivity in Babylon: in which also Baltassar was slain. Ier. 25. v. 12. & Ier. 29. v. 10. 2. Par. 36. v. 22.\f* \f + \fr 9:2 \ft Daniel seeing the seventieth year of captivity was come, in which God promised to deliver his people, Ier. 29. v. 10. prayed with great zeal, & confidence for their release.\f* \x + \xo 9:2 \xt Iere. 29. v. 10.\x*
\v 3 And I set my face to our Lord my God to pray and beseech in fastings, sackcloth, and ashes.
\v 4 And I prayed our Lord my God, and I confessed, and said: I beseech thee o Lord God great and terrible, which keepest covenant, & mercy to them that love thee, and keep thy commandments.
\v 5 We have sinned, we have done iniquity, we have dealt impiously, and have revolted: & we have declined from thy commandments, and judgements.
\v 6 We have not obeyed thy servants the prophets, that have spoken in thy name to our kings, to our princes, to our fathers, and to all the people of the land.
\v 7 To thee o Lord, justice: but to us confusion of face, as is today to the man of Juda, and to the inhabiters of Jerusalem, and to all Israel, to them that are near, and to them that are far off in all the lands, to which thou hast cast them out, for their iniquities in which they have sinned against thee.
\v 8 O Lord, to us confusion of face, to our princes, & to our fathers that have sinned.
\v 9 But to thee Lord our God mercy and propitiation, because we have revolted from thee:
\v 10 and have not heard the voice of the Lord our God, to walk in his law, which he gave us by his servants the prophets.
\v 11 And all Israel have transgressed thy law, and have declined from hearing thy voice, and the malediction hath distilled upon us, & the detestation, which is written in the book of Moyses the servant of God, because we have sinned to him. \x + \xo 9:11 \xt Deu. 17. v. 14.\x*
\v 12 And he hath established his words, which he spake upon us, and upon our princes, that judged us, that he would bring in upon us a great evil, such as never was under all the heaven, according to that which hath been done in Jerusalem.
\v 13 As it is written in the law of Moyses, all this evil is come upon us: and we besought not thy face o Lord our God, that we might return from our iniquities, & might think on thy truth.
\v 14 And our Lord hath watched upon the malice, and hath brought it upon us: just is the Lord our God in all his works, which he hath done: for we have not heard his voice.
\v 15 And now o Lord our God, which broughtest forth thy people out of the Land of Ægypt in a strong hand, & madest thee a name according to this day: we have sinned, we have done iniquity.
\v 16 O Lord according to all thy justice, but let thy wrath be turned away I beseech thee, and thy fury from thy city Jerusalem, & from thy holy mount. For by reason of our sins, and the iniquities of our fathers, Jerusalem, and thy people are a reproach to all round about us.
\v 17 Now therefore hear o our God the petition of thy servant, & his prayers: and shew thy face upon thy sanctuary, which is desert, for thine own sake.
\v 18 Incline my God thine ear, & hear: open thine eyes, and see our desolation, & the city upon which thy name is invocated: for neither in our justifications do we prostrate prayers before thy face, but in thy many commiserations.
\v 19 Hear o Lord, be pacified o Lord: attend & do, delay not for thine own sake my God: because thy name is invocated upon thy city, & upon thy people.
\v 20 And when I yet spake, & prayed, and confessed my sins, and the sins of my people of Israel, and did prostrate my prayers in the sight of my God, for the holy mount of my God:
\v 21 as I was yet speaking in prayer, lo the man Gabriel, whom I had seen in the vision from the beginning, quickly flying touched me in the time of the evening sacrifice.
\v 22 And he taught me, and spake to me, & said: Daniel now am I come forth to teach thee, and that thou mightest understand.
\v 23 From the beginning of thy prayers the word came forth: and I am come to shew it to thee, because thou art a man of desires: and do thou mark the word, and understand the vision. \f + \fr 9:23 \ft This singular devotion with austere works of penance & zeal of his country merited this commendable title to be called, The man of desires.\f*
\v 24 Seventy weeks are abridged upon thy people, & upon thy holy city, that prevarication may be consummate, and sin take an end, & iniquity be abolished; and everlasting justice be brought; & vision be accomplished, and prophecy; & the Holy one of holies be anointed. \f + \fr 9:24 \ft And whereas he prayed particularly for the release of the Jews from captivity of Babylon, a far greater thing is promised & revealed to him, that within seventy weeks of years (that is 490. years) the Messias Christ will come & redeem mankind from captivity of sin & the devil.\f* \f + \fr 9:24 \ft These four things (v. 24.) Forgiveness of sins; Infusion of justice; Fulfilling of prophecies; & Anointed Holy of holies agree only to Christ.\f*
\v 25 Know therefore, & mark: From the going forth of the word, that Jerusalem be built again, unto Christ the prince, there shall be seven weeks, & sixty two weeks, & the street shall be built again, & the walls in straitness of the times. \f + \fr 9:25 \ft Hebdomas or Septenarius signifying seven, understood of days importeth a week: of years (as Levi. 25. ) seven years: so seventy weeks 490. years. S. Bed. li. de rat. temp. c. 6. 7. 8.\f* \f + \fr 9:25 \ft * troublesome times.\f*
\v 26 And after sixty two weeks Christ shall be slain: and it shall not be his people, that shall deny him. And the city, & the sanctuary shall the people dissipate with the prince to come: & the end thereof waste, & after the end of the battle the appointed desolation.
\v 27 And he will confirm the covenant to many, one week: and in the half of the week shall the host & the sacrifice fail: and there shall be in the temple the abomination of desolation: & even to the consummation, and to the end shall the desolation endure. \x + \xo 9:27 \xt Mat. 24.\x*
\c 10
\p
\v 1 IN the third year of Cyrus king of the Persians, a word was revealed to Daniel surnamed Baltassar, and a true word, and great strength: & he understood the word: for there is need of understanding in vision. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Pharao had a vision in sleep, Gen. 41. Baltasar waking, saw a hand writing in the wall, Dan. 5. but neither of them understood their visions, and therefore were not Prophets. Joseph understood the former, & Daniel this other, and so, they were Prophets. For as this text teacheth, understanding is required that a vision be prophetical. S. Tho. 2. 2. q. 175. a. 2. & 4.\f*
\v 2 In those days I Daniel mourned the days of three weeks,
\v 3 desiderable bread I did not eat, and flesh and wine entered not into my mouth, yea neither with ointment was I anointed: till the days of three weeks were accomplished.
\v 4 And in the four & twentieth day of the first month I was by the great river, which is Tigris.
\v 5 And I lifted up mine eyes, & I saw: and behold a man clothed with linen cloths, & his reins girded with the finest gold:
\v 6 and his body as it were the chrysolithus, and his face as the form of lightning, and his eyes as a burning lamp: and his arms, & the parts that are downward even to the feet, as it were the form of glistering brass: and the voice of his word as the voice of a multitude.
\v 7 And I Daniel alone saw the vision: moreover the men that were with me, saw it not, but exceeding terror fell upon them, and they fled away, and hid themselves.
\v 8 And I being left alone saw this great vision: and there remained no strength in me, yea and my shape of countenance was changed in me, and I withered, neither had any strength.
\v 9 And I heard the voice of his words: and hearing I lay astonished upon my face, and my visage cleaved to the ground.
\v 10 And behold a hand touched me, and lifted me up upon my knees, and upon the joints of my hands.
\v 11 And he said to me: Daniel thou man of desires, understand the words, that I speak to thee, and stand in thy place: for now am I sent to thee. And when he had said this word to me, I stood trembling. \f + \fr 10:11 \ft The Angel repeateth this honourable new title to encourage him being sore frighted.\f*
\v 12 And he said to me: Fear not Daniel: because since the first day that thou didst set thy heart to understand to afflict thyself in the sight of thy God, thy words have been heard: and I am come for thy words. \f + \fr 10:12 \ft prayers.\f*
\v 13 But the prince of the kingdom of the Persians resisted me one and twenty days: and behold Michael one of the chief princes came to aid me, and I tarried there by the king of the Persians. \f + \fr 10:13 \ft The Angel guardian of Persia. S. Ierom, S. Theodoret. S. Gregory.\f* \f + \fr 10:13 \ft This Angel for his office sake, not yet knowing God's will in this particular, prayed that the Jews might remain among the Persians for their edification and spiritual good.\f*
\v 14 But I am come to teach thee what things shall come to thy people in the later days, because as yet the vision unto days.
\v 15 And when he spake to me in these manner of words, I cast down my countenance to the ground, and held my peace.
\v 16 And behold as it were the similitude of the son of man touched my lips, and opening my mouth I spake, and said to him, that stood before me: My Lord, in thy vision my joints are dissolved, and no strength hath remained in me.
\v 17 And how can the servant of my Lord speak with my Lord? for no strength is remaining in me, yea & my breath is stopped.
\v 18 Again therefore there touched me as it were the vision of a man, and strengthened me,
\v 19 and he said: Fear not o man of desires, Peace be to thee: take courage & be strong. And when he spake with me, I received strength, and said: Speak my Lord, because thou hast strengthened me.
\v 20 And he said: Doest thou know wherefore I am come to thee? and now I will return, that I may fight against the prince of the Persians. When I therefore went forth, there appeared the prince of the Greeks coming. \f + \fr 10:20 \ft Daniel's proper Angel joined his prayers with him for the delivery of the Jews from captivity.\f*
\v 21 But yet I will tell thee that which is expressed in the scripture of truth: and none is my helper in all these, but Michael your prince. \f + \fr 10:21 \ft S. Michael the guardian Angel of the whole Church also prayed for the same purpose.\f*
\c 11
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* I from the first year of Darius the Mede stood that he might be strengthened, and made strong. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft The Angel prosecuting his speech to the Prophet sheweth that he had prayed for the King of Persians, from the first time after the overthrow of Babylon, seeing him well affected towards the Jews, as was also the next King Cyrus, who indeed released them.\f*
\v 2 And now I will declare the truth unto thee. Behold three kings as yet shall stand in Persia, and the fourth shall be enriched with exceeding riches above all: & when he is grown mighty in his riches, he shall raise up all against the kingdom of Greece. \f + \fr 11:2 \ft * Cambyses. 1. Smerdes magus. Darius Histaspis.\f* \f + \fr 11:2 \ft * Xerxes.\f*
\v 3 But there shall rise a strong king, and shall rule with much power: and he shall do what shall please him. \f + \fr 11:3 \ft Alexander.\f*
\v 4 And when he shall stand, his kingdom shall be broken, and it shall be divided into the four winds of heaven: but not unto his posterity, nor according to his mightiness wherewith he ruled. For his kingdom shall be rent even unto foreigners, beside these. \f + \fr 11:4 \ft Scarcely touching other successors of Alexander, the holy scripture here prophesieth of the Kings of Ægypt on the south side of Jury; and Syrians on the North: by whose wars the Jews were most molested.\f* \f + \fr 11:4 \ft * come to his height.\f*
\v 5 And the king of the South shall be made strong, & there shall of his princes prevail above him, and he shall rule in dominion: for his dominion shall be much. \f + \fr 11:5 \ft Every prophecy (saith S. Iren. li. 4. c. 43.) before it be fulfilled is ænigma, a riddle, or obscure proposition. But when it is past may more easily, sometimes certainly be interpreted. So by histories of things now past he gathereth very probably that by this King of the south was understood Ptolomeus son of Lagus King of Ægypt.\f* \f + \fr 11:5 \ft His son called Ptolomeus Philadelphus excelled his father in power and magnificence.\f* \f + \fr 11:5 \ft King of Ægypt.\f*
\v 6 And after the end of years they shall be confederated: and the daughter of the king of the South shall come to the king of the North to make amity, and shall not obtain the strength of the arm, neither shall his seed stand: and she shall be delivered, and they that brought her, her youngmen and they that strengthened her in the times. \f + \fr 11:6 \ft This King of the North seemeth to be Antiochus Theos King of Syria.\f* \f + \fr 11:6 \ft King of Syria.\f*
\v 7 And there shall stand of the bud of her roots a plant: and he shall come with an army, and shall enter the province of the king of the North: and he shall abuse them, and shall obtain. \f + \fr 11:7 \ft Ptolomeus Evergetes King of Ægypt invaded and spoiled Syria.\f*
\v 8 Moreover also their gods, and sculptiles, the precious vessels also of gold, and silver, he shall carry away captive into Ægypt: he shall prevail against the king of the North.
\v 9 And the king of the South shall enter into the kingdom, and shall return to his own land.
\v 10 And his sons shall be provoked, and they shall gather a multitude of very many hosts: and he shall come hastening, and overflowing: and he shall return and be stirred up, and he shall join battle with his force. \f + \fr 11:10 \ft Seleucus Ceraunus, and Antiochus Magnus sons of Seleucus Callinicus shall raise new wars against Ptolomeus Philopator King of Ægypt, but the elder brother being slain in the way, Antiochus shall prosecute the war.\f*
\v 11 And the king of the South being provoked shall go forth, and shall fight against the king of the North, & shall prepare an exceeding great multitude, and a multitude shall be given into his hands.
\v 12 And he shall take a multitude, and his heart shall be exalted, and he shall overthrow many thousands: but he shall not prevail. \f + \fr 11:12 \ft He shall invade and kill many, but not prevail.\f*
\v 13 For the king of the North shall return, and shall prepare a multitude much greater than before: & in the end of times, & years, he shall come hastening with a great host, and riches exceeding much.
\v 14 And in those times many shall rise up against the king of the South, the children also of the prevaricators of thy people shall be extolled to fulfill the vision, and they shall fall. \f + \fr 11:14 \ft Many Jews deceived by Onias flying into Ægypt shall erect a temple and sacrifice, falsely avouching that they fulfil the prophecy of Isaie. ch. 19. v. 19.\f* \x + \xo 11:14 \xt Isa. 19. v. 19.\x*
\v 15 And the king of the North shall come, and shall cast up a mount, and shall take the best fenced cities: & the arms of the South shall not sustain, and his chosen shall rise up to resist, & there shall be no strength.
\v 16 And he shall do coming upon him according to his pleasure, and there shall be none to stand against his face: and he shall stand in a noble land, & it shall be consumed in his hand.
\v 17 And he shall set his face to come to possess all his kingdom, & he shall do right things with him: and he shall give unto him a daughter of women, to overthrow it: and she shall not stand neither shall she be his.
\v 18 And he shall turn his face to the islands, & shall take many: and he shall make the prince of his reproach to cease, and his reproach shall be returned upon him.
\v 19 And he shall turn his face to the empire of his own land, and he shall stumble, and fall, & shall not be found.
\v 20 And there shall stand in his place one most vile, & unworthy of kingly honour: & in few days he shall be destroyed, not in fury nor in battle.
\v 21 And there shall stand in his place one despised, and kingly honour shall not be given him: and he shall come secretly, and shall obtain the kingdom by fraud. \f + \fr 11:21 \ft According to the history all expositers understand this of Antiochus Epiphanes, who lived and died basely: but mystically of Antichrist, very potent & glorious in this world, yet shall have base beginning and an ignominious end.\f*
\v 22 And the arms of him that fighteth shall be expugned from before his face, and shall be broken: moreover also the prince of the league. \f + \fr 11:22 \ft This title Prince of the league or covenant, pertaineth directly to Antichrist: who will join himself with the Jews pretending to observe the law of Moyses and so they will receive him as their Messias. Ioan. 5. v. 43. S. Ireneus li. 5. c. 25. S. Ierom. & alii.\f*
\v 23 And after the amities, he shall work deceit with him: and he shall go up, and shall overcome with few people.
\v 24 And he shall enter abundant and plentiful cities: & he shall do things that his fathers never did, & his fathers' fathers: their robberies, and prey, & riches he shall dissipate, and shall devise devices against the best fenced: and this until a time.
\v 25 And his strength & his heart shall be stirred up against the king of the South in a great army: and the king of the South shall be provoked to battle with many aids, and exceeding strong: & they shall not stand because they shall take counsels against him.
\v 26 And they that eat bread with him, shall destroy him, and his army shall be oppressed: & there shall fall slain very many.
\v 27 The heart also of the two kings shall be to evil, and at one table they shall speak lies, and they shall not prosper: because as yet the end unto another time.
\v 28 And he shall return into his land with much riches: and his heart against the holy testament, and he shall prosper and shall return into his own land.
\v 29 At the time appointed he shall return, and he shall come to the South, and the later end shall not be like to the former.
\v 30 And there shall come upon him galleys, and the Romans, and he shall be strucken, and shall return, and shall fret against the testament of the sanctuary, and he shall speed: and shall return, and shall devise against them, that have forsaken the testament of the sanctuary.
\v 31 And of him shall stand arms, and shall pollute the sanctuary of strength, and shall take away the continual sacrifice: and they shall give abomination into desolation. \f + \fr 11:31 \ft Even in the hottest persecution of Antiochus, Nero, or Antichrist, some shall constantly confess true religion.\f*
\v 32 And the impious against the testament shall dissemble fraudulently: but the people that knoweth their God, shall obtain, and shall do.
\v 33 And the learned in the people shall teach very many: and they shall fall by sword, and by flame, and by captivity, and by spoil of days.
\v 34 And when they are fallen, they shall be relieved with a little aid: and very many shall be joined to them feignedly.
\v 35 And of the learned there shall fall, that they may be tried, and may be chosen, and made white even to the time prefixed: because yet there shall be another time.
\v 36 And the king shall do according to his will, and shall be elevated, & magnified against every god: and against the God of gods he shall speak magnifical things, & shall be directed, till the wrath be accomplished: for the determination is made.
\v 37 And the God of his fathers he shall not account of: and he shall be in the concupiscences of women, neither shall he care for any of the gods: because he shall rise up against all things.
\v 38 But god Maozim he shall worship in his place: and the god whom his fathers knew not, he shall worship with gold, and silver, and precious stone, and precious things. \f + \fr 11:38 \ft The god of power or strength, either Jupiter the Grecians' great god, or their own strength, wherein Antiochus, & Antichrist shall trust.\f*
\v 39 And he shall do it to fence Maozim with a strange god, whom he acknowledged, and he shall multiply glory, and shall give them power in many, and shall divide the land gratis.
\v 40 And in the time prefixed shall the king of the South make battle against him, & as a tempest shall the king of the North come against him in chariots, and in horsemen, and in a great navy, and he shall enter the lands, and shall destroy, and pass through.
\v 41 And he shall enter into the glorious land, and many shall fall: but these only shall be saved out of his hand, Edom, and Moab, and the beginning of the children of Ammon.
\v 42 And he shall lay his hand upon the lands: and the Land of Ægypt shall not escape.
\v 43 And he shall rule over the treasures of gold, and of silver, and in all the precious things of Ægypt: through Libya also, and Æthiopia he shall pass.
\v 44 And a bruit shall trouble him from the East, and from the North: and he shall come in a great multitude to destroy and kill very many.
\v 45 And he shall pitch his tabernacle Apadno between the seas, upon a mount glorious and holy: and he shall come even to the top thereof, and no man shall help him. \f + \fr 11:45 \ft His royal tabernacle or palace, between the dead sea & the Mediterranean.\f*
\c 12
\p
\v 1 \sc But\sc* in that time shall rise up Michael the great prince, who standeth for the children of thy people: and a time shall come such as hath not been from the time since nations began even until that time. And in that time shall thy people be saved, every one that shall be found written in the book. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft S. Michael the Guardian Angel & protector of the Jews in the old Testament. c. 10. v. 13. & 21. & now of the Church of Christ, will defend the same against Antichrist invisibly as the Ecclesiastical pastors shall do visibly.\f*
\v 2 And many of those, that sleep in the dust of the earth, shall awake: some unto life everlasting, & others unto reproach to see it always. \f + \fr 12:2 \ft All shall rise in body, but all shall not be changed into better. 1. Cor. 15. v. 51.\f*
\v 3 But they that be learned shall shine as the brightness of the firmament: and they that instruct many to justice, as stars unto perpetual eternities. \f + \fr 12:3 \ft Aglorious Aureola or accidental reward (besides the essential beatitude) shall be given to those that duly perform the office of pastors, in teaching others, as there is another like to Martyrs, & another to Virgins.\f* \f + \fr 12:3 \ft * in the law of God.\f*
\v 4 But thou Daniel shut up the words, and seal the book, even to the time appointed: very many shall pass over, and there shall be manifest knowledge. \f + \fr 12:4 \ft Daniel's prophecy is shut & sealed, not to be interpreted by human wit, but by the spirit of God, wherewith the Church is illuminated, taught, governed, moved, & vivificated: S. Iero. in Gal.\f*
\v 5 And I Daniel saw, and behold there stood as it were two others: one on this side upon the bank of the river, and another on that side, on the other bank of the river.
\v 6 And I said to the man, that was clothed with linen garments, that stood upon the waters of the river: How long the end of these marvels?
\v 7 And I heard the man, that was clothed with the linen garments, that stood upon the waters of the river, when he had lifted up his right hand, & his left hand unto heaven, and had sworn by him that liveth for ever, that unto a time, & times, & the half of a time. And when the dispersion of the hand of the holy people shall be accomplished, all these things shall be accomplished. \f + \fr 12:7 \ft Atime ordinarily signifieth one year, as ch. 4. v. 13. so here is signified the space of three years and a half, as. ch. 7. and Apo. 12. v. 14. &c.\f*
\v 8 And I heard, & understood not. And I said: My Lord, what shall be after these things?
\v 9 And he said: Go Daniel, because the words are shut up, and sealed until the prefixed time.
\v 10 Many shall be chosen, and made white, & shall be tried as fire: and the impious shall do impiously, neither shall all the impious understand, but the learned shall understand.
\v 11 And from the time when the continual sacrifice shall be taken away, and the abomination to desolation shall be set up, a thousand two hundred ninety days. \f + \fr 12:11 \ft From the taking away of the daily sacrifice, and placing of abomination (to wit the practice of heresy) to desolation, that is, abolishing of much as is possible, the holy Sacrifice of Mass, to the end of that persecution shall be 1290. days.\f* \x + \xo 12:11 \xt Mat. 24.\x*
\v 12 Blessed is he that expecteth, and cometh unto days a thousand three hundred thirty five. \f + \fr 12:12 \ft Why 45. days are added to the former number, is marvelous obscure: neither may we presume amongst diverse expositions, to censure which seemeth most probable.\f*
\v 13 But thou go, until the time prefixed: and thou shalt rest, and stand in thy lot unto the end of the days. \f + \fr 12:13 \ft But we are content to go away with Daniel ( v. 9. and 13. ) without further searching the profound sense of so high mysteries.\f*
\c 13
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there was a man dwelling in Babylon, and his name Joakim: \f + \fr 13:1 \ft S. Athanasius in Synopsi, reciteth this history in the beginning of Daniel. And S. Aug. ser. 242. de tem. supposeth that Daniel about the age of twelve years endued with the spirit of prophecy, discovered the malicious falsehood of them, that accused Susanna.\f*
\v 2 & he took a wife named Susanna, the daughter of Helcias exceeding fair, and fearing God.
\v 3 For her parents being just, instructed their daughter according to the law of Moyses.
\v 4 And Joakim was very rich, and he had an orchard near unto his house: and to him the Jews resorted together, because he was the more honorable of all.
\v 5 And there were two ancients appointed judges in that year, of whom our Lord spake: That iniquities came out of Babylon from the senior judges, that seemed to rule the people. \f + \fr 13:5 \ft In the transmigration which was made in the third year of Ioakim King of Juda, the Jews were better entreated, and had their own judicial tribunal, and other privileges, until the captivity, which happened about 19. years after, in the eleventh year of Sedecias. At which time they were brought into much more bondage.\f*
\v 6 These frequented the house of Joakim, and all that had judgements came to them.
\v 7 And when the people returned at noon, Susanna went in, and walked in her husband's orchard.
\v 8 and the ancients saw her daily going in, and walking: and they were inflamed to the concupiscence of her:
\v 9 and they subverted their sense, and declined their eyes that they would not see heaven, nor remember just judgements.
\v 10 They were both therefore wounded with the love of her, neither did they shew their grief one to the other:
\v 11 for they were ashamed to shew one another their concupiscence, being desirous to lie with her:
\v 12 and they watched every day carefully to see her. And one said to the other:
\v 13 Let us go home, because it is the hour of dinner. And going forth they departed one from another.
\v 14 And when they were returned, they came into one place: and asking of each other the cause, they confessed their concupiscence: and then in commune they appointed a time, when they might find her alone.
\v 15 And it came to pass, when they observed a fit day, she went in on a time as yesterday and the day before, with two maids only, & would be washed in the orchard: for it was an hot season.
\v 16 And there was none there, but the two ancients hid, & beholding her.
\v 17 She therefore said to the maids: Fetch me oil, and washing balls, and shut the doors of the orchard, that I may be washed.
\v 18 And they did as she had commanded: and they shut the doors of the orchard, and went out by a back door to fetch the thing that she had commanded; and they knew not that the ancients were hid within.
\v 19 But when the maids were gone forth, the two ancients arose, and ran to her, and said:
\v 20 Lo the doors of the orchard be shut, and nobody seeth us, and we are in the concupiscence of thee: wherefore consent to us, and lie with us.
\v 21 and if thou wilt not, we will give testimony against thee, that there was a young man with thee, and for this cause thou didst send out thy maids from thee.
\v 22 Susanna sighed, and said: Perplexities are to me on every side: for if I shall do this, it is death to me: and if I do it not, I shall not escape your hands.
\v 23 But it is better for me without the act to fall into your hands, than to sin in the sight of our Lord.
\v 24 And Susanna cried out with a loud voice: but the ancients also cried out against her.
\v 25 And one ran to the door of the orchard, and opened it.
\v 26 when the servants therefore of the house had heard the cry in the orchard, they rushed in by the back door, to see what it was.
\v 27 And after the ancients spake, the servants were ashamed exceedingly: because never had there been such a word said of Susanna. And the morrow came.
\v 28 And when the people was come to Joakim her husband, the two ancients also came full of unjust cogitation against Susanna, to put her to death.
\v 29 And they said before the people: Send to Susanna daughter of Helcias the wife of Joakim. And forthwith they sent. \f + \fr 13:29 \ft For more colour of just proceeding, these wicked men gave their false testimony & sentence before the people.\f*
\v 30 And she came with her parents, and children, and all her kin.
\v 31 Moreover Susanna was exceeding delicate, and beautiful of face.
\v 32 But those wicked men commanded that she should be uncovered (for she was covered) that so at least they might be satisfied with her beauty.
\v 33 Her friends therefore wept, & all that had known her.
\v 34 But the two ancients rising up in the midst of the people, laid their hands upon her head.
\v 35 Who weeping looked up to heaven, for her heart had confidence in our Lord.
\v 36 And the ancients said: When we walked alone in the orchard, this woman came in with two maids, and shut the doors of the orchard: and she sent away the maids from her.
\v 37 And a young man that was hid came to her, and lay with her.
\v 38 But we being in a corner of the orchard, seeing the iniquity, ran to them, and saw them lie together.
\v 39 And him indeed we could not take, because he was stronger than we, and opening the doors he lept out:
\v 40 but her when we apprehended, we asked what youngman it was, and she would not tell us, of this thing we are witnesses.
\v 41 The multitude believed them as the ancients and the judges of the people, and they condemned her to death. \f + \fr 13:41 \ft The people gave their opinions that she deserved death, but the false Judges gave sentence. For so the form of the law required, which they pretended to fulfill. Lev. 20. Deut. 22.\f*
\v 42 But Susanna cried out with a loud voice, and said: Eternal God, which art the knower of hidden things before they come to pass,
\v 43 thou knowest that they have borne false witness against me: and lo I die, whereas I have done none of these things, which these men have maliciously forged against me.
\v 44 And our Lord heard her voice.
\v 45 and when she was led to death, our Lord raised up the holy spirit of a young boy, whose name was Daniel: \f + \fr 13:45 \ft Daniel by the gift of prophecy saw & declared that she was innocent.\f*
\v 46 and he cried out with a loud voice: I am clean from the blood of this woman. \f + \fr 13:46 \ft Whereas therefore the people had consented to her death, he denied his consent, & undertook to convince the false witnesses: as he did. v. 54. & 58.\f*
\v 47 And all the people turning to him, said: What is this word, that thou hast spoken?
\v 48 Who when he stood in the midst of them, said: So foolish ye children of Israel, not judging, nor discerning that which is the truth, have you condemned the daughter of Israel?
\v 49 Return ye to judgement, because they have spoken false testimony against her.
\v 50 The people therefore returned with speed, and the ancients said to him: Come, and sit in the midst of us, and tell us: because God hath given thee the honour of old age.
\v 51 And Daniel said to the people: Separate them far one from another, and I will discover them.
\v 52 When they were therefore divided one from the other, he called one of them, and said to him: O thou inveterated of evil days, now are thy sins come, which thou didst commit before:
\v 53 judging unjust judgements, oppressing innocents, and dismissing offenders, our Lord saying: The innocent and the just thou shalt not kill. \x + \xo 13:53 \xt Iere. 22. v. 3. Exo. 23. v. 7.\x*
\v 54 Now then if thou sawest her, tell under what tree thou sawest them talking together. Who said: Under a schine tree.
\v 55 And Daniel said: Well hast thou lied against thine own head: for behold the Angel of God taking the sentence of him, shall cut thee in the midst.
\v 56 And removing him away, he commanded that the other should come, and he said to him: Seed of Chanaan, and not of Juda, beauty hath deceived thee, and concupiscence hath subverted thy heart:
\v 57 so did you to the daughters of Israel, and they fearing spake to you: but the daughter of Juda did not abide your iniquity.
\v 58 Now therefore tell me, under what tree thou tookest them speaking one to another. Who said: Under a prine tree.
\v 59 And Daniel said to him: Well hast thou also lied against thine own head: for the Angel of our Lord tarrieth, having a sword, that he may cut thee in the midst, and kill you.
\v 60 Therefore all the assembly cried out with a loud voice, and they blessed God, which saveth them that hope in him.
\v 61 And they rose up against the two elders (for Daniel had convinced them by their own mouth to have given false testimony) and they did to them as they had dealt naughtily against their neighbour,
\v 62 to do according to the law of Moyses: & they killed them, and innocent blood was saved in that day. \x + \xo 13:62 \xt Deu. 19. v. 19.\x*
\v 63 But Helcias, and his wife praised God, for their daughter Susanna, with Joakim her husband, and all her kin, because there was no unhonest thing found in her.
\v 64 And Daniel became great in the sight of the people from that day, & thence forward. \f + \fr 13:64 \ft By this first prophetical act, Daniel began worthily to be esteemed.\f*
\v 65 And king Astyages was laid to his fathers, & Cyrus the Persian received his kingdom. \f + \fr 13:65 \ft This last verse, of Astyages otherwise called Darius, and of Cyrus succeeding him, pertaineth to the ninth chapter. And here mention is made of them, to signify that Daniel beginning to prophesy in his childhood, continued even to old age. For between this history of Susanna and the death of Darius were about ninety years.\f*
\c 14
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* Daniel was the king's guest, and honoured above all his friends. \f + \fr 14:1 \ft It seemeth most probable that this King was Evilmerodach, who favoured the Jews, and delivered Jechonias (otherwise called Ioachin) out of prison. 4. Reg. 25. v. 27.\f*
\v 2 There was also an idol among the Babylonians named Bel: and there were bestowed on him every day of flour twelve arctabæs, and forty sheep, and of wine six great pots. \f + \fr 14:2 \ft * amphoræ.\f* \x + \xo 14:2 \xt Gen. 10. v. 10.\x*
\v 3 The king also did worship him, and went every day to adore him: But Daniel adored his God. & the king said to him: Why dost thou not adore Bel. \f + \fr 14:3 \ft Which supposed, Daniel was now about the age of 55. years. For being carried into Babylon at the age of ten years, was there 8. years before Ioachin, who was there 37. years before he was delivered from prison, which make in all 55.\f*
\v 4 Who answering, said to him: Because I worship not idols made with hand, but the living God, that created heaven, and earth, and hath power over all flesh.
\v 5 And the king said to him: Doeth not Bel seem unto thee to be a living God? Seest thou not how much he eateth and drinketh every day?
\v 6 And Daniel smiling said: Be not deceived o king: For this same is within of clay, and without of brass, neither hath he eaten at any time.
\v 7 And the king being wrath called his priests, & said to them: Unless you tell me, who it is that eateth these expenses, you shall die.
\v 8 But if you shew, that Bel eateth these things Daniel shall die, because he hath blasphemed against Bel. And Daniel said to the king: Be it done according to thy word.
\v 9 And the priests of Bel were seventy, beside their wives, and little ones, & children. And the king came with Daniel into the temple of Bel.
\v 10 And the priests of Bel said: Behold we go forth: & thou o king set the meats, & mingle the wine, & shut the door, & seal it with thy ring:
\v 11 and when thou shalt come in the morning, unless thou find all eaten of Bel, dying we will die, or Daniel that hath lied against us.
\v 12 And they contemned, because they had made under the table a secret entrance, & by it they came in always, and devoured those things.
\v 13 It came to pass therefore after they were gone out, the king set the meats before Bel: & Daniel commanded his servants, and they brought ashes, and he sifted them over all the temple before the king: and going forth they shut the door, and sealing it with the king's ring, they departed.
\v 14 But the priests went in by night, according to their custom, and their wives, and their children: and they did eat, and drink all.
\v 15 And the king arose in the first break of day, and Daniel with him.
\v 16 And the king said: Are the seals safe, Daniel? Who answered: Safe o king.
\v 17 And forthwith when he had opened the door, the king looking on the table, cried out with a loud voice: Great art thou o Bel, and there is not any deceit with thee.
\v 18 And Daniel laughed: and he held the king that he should not go in: and he said: Behold the pavement, mark whose steps these are.
\v 19 And the king said: I see the steps of men, & women, and of infants. And the king was angry.
\v 20 Then apprehended he the priests, & their wives, & their children: and they shewed him secret little doors by which they came in, & consumed the things that were on the table.
\v 21 The king therefore slew them, & he delivered Bel into the power of Daniel: who overthrew him, & his temple.
\v 22 And there was a great dragon in that place, & the Babylonians worshipped him. \f + \fr 14:22 \ft Not only the Babylonians as is manifest in many places, but also the Romans and most nations worshipped Bel for a great god: But it is more wonderful that both the Chaldees and the Romans, otherwise most wise, worshipped a serpent, or dragon, a beast naturally most hating men, & most abhorred by all men. The cause of this blindness can be no other but God's just punishment, suffering them for their abominable pride, and other sins to fall into sottish conceits, as to think, that serpents could either greatly benefit them, or by such worship be appeased, and cease from annoying them. As Valerius writeth. li. 1. c. 8. S. Augustine also li. 14. c. 11. Civit. & many others testify the same.\f*
\v 23 And the king said to Daniel: Lo now thou canst not say, that this same is not a living god: adore him therefore.
\v 24 And Daniel said: The Lord my God I do adore: because he is the living God:
\v 25 but thou o king give me licence, and I will kill the dragon without sword and club. And the king said: I give thee licence.
\v 26 Daniel therefore took pitch, and fat, and hairs, and sod them together: & he made lumps, and gave into the dragon's mouth, & the dragon burst in sunder. And he said: Lo whom you worshipped.
\v 27 Which when the Babylonians had heard, they were wrath exceedingly: and being gathered together against the king, they said: The king is become a Jew. Bel he hath destroyed, the dragon he hath killed, & he hath slain the priests.
\v 28 And they said when they were come to the king: Deliver us Daniel, otherwise we will kill thee, & thy house.
\v 29 The king therefore saw that they pressed upon him vehemently: and compelled by necessity he delivered Daniel to them.
\v 30 Who cast him into the lake of lions, and he was there six days.
\v 31 Moreover in the lake were seven lions, & there were given to them two bodies every day, & two sheep: and they were not given unto them, that they might devour Daniel.
\v 32 And there was Habacuc a prophet in Jewry, & he had boiled broth, & had broken bread in a bowl: and he went into the field, to carry it to the reapers. \f + \fr 14:32 \ft Although about 20. years before, there was no Prophet in Jury (ch. 3. v. 38.) yet now this Habacuc was endued with the spirit of prophecy. As for Habacuc, the eighth in order of the less Prophets, he prophesied before the captivity: yea before the Chaldees became a Monarchy. As appeareth Hab. 1. v. 6.\f*
\v 33 And the Angel of our Lord said to Habacuc: Carry the dinner which thou hast, into Babylon to Daniel, who is in the lake of lions.
\v 34 And Habacuc said: Lord, Babylon I have not seen, and the lake I know not.
\v 35 And the Angel of our Lord took him by the top of his head, and carried him by the hair of his head, & put him into Babylon over the lake in the force of his spirit.
\v 36 And Habacuc cried, saying: Daniel, take the dinner that God hath sent to thee.
\v 37 And Daniel said: Thou hast remembered me o God, and hast not forsaken them that love thee.
\v 38 And Daniel rising up did eat. Moreover the Angel of our Lord restored Habacuc forthwith in his place.
\v 39 The king therefore came the seventh day to lament Daniel: and he came to the lake, and looked in, and behold Daniel sitting in the midst of the lions.
\v 40 And the king cried out with a loud voice, saying: Great art thou o Lord the God of Daniel. And he drew him out of the lake of lions.
\v 41 But those that had been the cause of his perdition, he cast into the lake, and they were devoured in a moment before him.
\v 42 Then the king said: Let all inhabitants in the whole earth fear the God of Daniel: because he is the Saviour, doing signs, & marvels in the earth: who hath delivered Daniel out of the lions' den.
